  "prompt": "In genetics, what is an example of a monohybrid cross offspring?",
  "response": "A monohybrid cross involves the study of the inheritance of a single trait controlled by a pair of alleles. An example of a monohybrid cross offspring can be seen in Mendel's classic pea plant experiments.\n\n### Example:\n- **Parental Generation (P):**  \n  - One parent is homozygous dominant for a trait (e.g., **TT** for tall plants).  \n  - The other parent is homozygous recessive for the same trait (e.g., **tt** for short plants).  \n\n- **First Filial Generation (F1) Offspring:**  \n  - All offspring will be heterozygous for the trait (**Tt**).  \n  - Since **T** (tall) is dominant, all F1 offspring will exhibit the tall phenotype.  \n\nIf the F1 offspring (**Tt**) are self-crossed (monohybrid cross), the **Second Filial Generation (F2)** will show a 3:1 phenotypic ratio:  \n- **3 tall plants** (genotypes: **TT** or **Tt**)  \n- **1 short plant** (genotype: **tt**).  \n\nThus, an example of a monohybrid cross offspring in the F2 generation would be a tall plant (**Tt**) or a short plant (**tt**).",
